    passage: "Political scientist James C. Scott has argued that large-scale state-sponsored development projects — dams, collective farms, planned cities — frequently fail because they impose a simplified, top-down vision on complex local realities. Scott uses the term \"high modernism\" to describe the ideology behind such projects: an overconfidence in the ability of technical expertise and centralized planning to reshape society and nature according to rational blueprints. The failures, Scott contends, arise not from the incompetence of planners but from the inherent limitations of any centralized scheme to capture the rich, informal knowledge — what Scott calls \"mētis\" — that local communities develop through generations of practical experience. The schemes fail, in other words, precisely because they succeed in overriding the local adaptations that made things work.",
